         <abstract>
            <p>By classifying borderline income and expense items as ordinary or extraordinary, management can smooth the stream of ordinary income -- the variable believed to command the primary attention of investors. Because management possesses less than total flexibility in how it classifies borderline items, however, any attempt at smoothing will tend to be less than complete -- hence will result in positive correlation between ordinary income and extraordinary income. The correlation observed for actual companies is significant and positive, suggesting the presence of income smoothing.</p>
          </abstract>
